{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dbe1456d-1e0a-4616-913a-e9f7d1c07318","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### To get the file off the pod:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, threadpool stats — useful to confirm the issue before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to network restrictions in the container, you can [sidecar-copy](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace) the tool binary in, or use **PerfView** / **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** from the host node since you have admin access.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"821ac475-1f95-4f47-9479-785d9b5a9dc6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"6016:35BDDE:25D0AE:2CB98E:69EAC4D5"},"id":"5e010038-9602-407d-938c-b523cb94be4f","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:18:23.869Z","parentId":"d219f4bf-63d1-4442-8a57-cd5d0a4f477a"}
